# Git Cheat Sheet

## ğŸ”‘ Basic Git Commands

* `git init` â†’ Initialize a new Git repository in the current directory.
* `git clone <repo_url>` â†’ Clone a remote repository locally.
* `git status` â†’ Check the status of your working directory (changes, staged files, etc.).
* `git add <file>` â†’ Add file(s) to the staging area.
* `git add .` â†’ Add all modified/untracked files to the staging area.
* `git commit -m "message"` â†’ Commit staged changes with a message.
* `git log` â†’ Show commit history.
* `git diff` â†’ Show changes between commits or working directory and staging area.

## ğŸŒ Remote Repository Commands

* `git remote -v` â†’ Show configured remote repositories.
* `git remote add origin <repo_url>` â†’ Link local repo to remote repo.
* `git push origin main` â†’ Push changes to remote branch.
* `git pull origin main` â†’ Fetch and merge changes from remote branch.
* `git fetch` â†’ Download changes but donâ€™t merge them yet.

## ğŸŒ¿ Branching & Merging

* `git branch` â†’ List branches.
* `git branch <branch_name>` â†’ Create a new branch.
* `git checkout <branch_name>` â†’ Switch to another branch.
* `git switch <branch_name>` â†’ Alternate way to switch branches.
* `git checkout -b <branch_name>` â†’ Create and switch to new branch.
* `git merge <branch_name>` â†’ Merge branch into current branch.
* `git branch -d <branch_name>` â†’ Delete branch.

## ğŸ”„ Undoing & Resetting

* `git reset <file>` â†’ Unstage a file.
* `git reset --hard <commit_id>` â†’ Reset repo to a specific commit (discard changes).
* `git revert <commit_id>` â†’ Create a new commit that undoes a specific commit.
* `git checkout -- <file>` â†’ Discard changes in a file.

## ğŸ¯ Other Useful Commands

* `git stash` â†’ Save changes temporarily without committing.
* `git stash pop` â†’ Reapply the stashed changes.
* `git tag <tag_name>` â†’ Create a tag (useful for releases).
* `git show <commit_id>` â†’ Show details of a commit.
* `git blame <file>` â†’ Show who made changes line by line.
